      <title>Possible government shutdown looms. And, tips to help with seasonal depression</title>
      <author>Brittney Melton</author>
      <link>https://www.npr.org/2024/12/19/g-s1-39022/up-first-newsletter-tiktok-supreme-court-possible-holiday-government-shutdown-syria-changes</link>
      <comments>https://text.npr.org/2024/12/19/g-s1-39022/up-first-newsletter-tiktok-supreme-court-possible-holiday-government-shutdown-syria-changes</comments>
      <guid isPermaLink="true">https://www.npr.org/2024/12/19/g-s1-39022/up-first-newsletter-tiktok-supreme-court-possible-holiday-government-shutdown-syria-changes</guid>
      <pubDate>Thu, 19 Dec 2024 13:00:35 +0000</pubDate>
      <description>&lt;div id="storytext" class="storytext storylocation linkLocation"&gt;       &lt;p&gt;&lt;em&gt;Good morning. You're reading the Up First newsletter. &lt;/em&gt;&lt;a href="https://www.npr.org/newsletter/news" target="_blank"&gt;Subscribe&lt;/a&gt;&lt;em&gt; here to get it delivered to your inbox, and &lt;/em&gt;&lt;a href="https://www.npr.org/podcasts/510318/up-first/" target="_blank"&gt;listen&lt;/a&gt;&lt;em&gt; to the Up First podcast for all the news you need to start your day.&lt;/em&gt;&lt;br&gt;&lt;/p&gt;   &lt;h3 class="edTag"&gt;Today's top stories&lt;/h3&gt;   &lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;TikTok and the Department of Justice are headed to the Supreme Court, where justices could decide whether a law banning the app next month unless it is sold is constitutional. &lt;/strong&gt;The high court accepted TikTok's emergency request to hear arguments about the law and the justices moved quickly and deliberately. Oral arguments have been &lt;a href="https://www.npr.org/2024/12/18/nx-s1-5233027/supreme-court-to-review-tiktok-ban" target="_blank"&gt;set for Jan. 10&lt;/a&gt;, which is nine days before the app's sell-or-be-banned deadline.&lt;/p&gt;   &lt;div id="res1237843733" class="bucketwrap image large"&gt;             &lt;div     class="imagewrap has-source-dimensions"     data-crop-type=""     style="         --source-width: 2587;         --source-height: 1455;     " &gt;         &lt;picture&gt;             &lt;source srcset="https://media.npr.org/assets/img/2024/03/11/ap24071617990627_wide-ea6040568f9ae3ac2cd3d8140014bf63d03891bb.jpg?s=400&amp;c=85&amp;f=webp 400w, https://media.npr.org/assets/img/2024/03/11/ap24071617990627_wide-ea6040568f9ae3ac2cd3d8140014bf63d03891bb.jpg?s=600&amp;c=85&amp;f=webp 600w, https://media.npr.org/assets/img/2024/03/11/ap24071617990627_wide-ea6040568f9ae3ac2cd3d8140014bf63d03891bb.jpg?s=800&amp;c=85&amp;f=webp 800w, https://media.npr.org/assets/img/2024/03/11/ap24071617990627_wide-ea6040568f9ae3ac2cd3d8140014bf63d03891bb.jpg?s=900&amp;c=85&amp;f=webp 900w, https://media.npr.org/assets/img/2024/03/11/ap24071617990627_wide-ea6040568f9ae3ac2cd3d8140014bf63d03891bb.jpg?s=1200&amp;c=85&amp;f=webp 1200w, https://media.npr.org/assets/img/2024/03/11/ap24071617990627_wide-ea6040568f9ae3ac2cd3d8140014bf63d03891bb.jpg?s=1600&amp;c=85&amp;f=webp 1600w, https://media.npr.org/assets/img/2024/03/11/ap24071617990627_wide-ea6040568f9ae3ac2cd3d8140014bf63d03891bb.jpg?s=1800&amp;c=85&amp;f=webp 1800w" data-template="https://media.npr.org/assets/img/2024/03/11/ap24071617990627_wide-ea6040568f9ae3ac2cd3d8140014bf63d03891bb.jpg?s={width}&amp;c={quality}&amp;f={format}" sizes="(min-width: 1300px) 763px, (min-width: 1025px) calc(100vw - 496px), (min-width: 768px) calc(100vw - 171px), calc(100vw - 30px)" class="img" type="image/webp" /&gt;             &lt;source srcset="https://media.npr.org/assets/img/2024/03/11/ap24071617990627_wide-ea6040568f9ae3ac2cd3d8140014bf63d03891bb.jpg?s=400&amp;c=85&amp;f=jpeg 400w, https://media.npr.org/assets/img/2024/03/11/ap24071617990627_wide-ea6040568f9ae3ac2cd3d8140014bf63d03891bb.jpg?s=600&amp;c=85&amp;f=jpeg 600w, https://media.npr.org/assets/img/2024/03/11/ap24071617990627_wide-ea6040568f9ae3ac2cd3d8140014bf63d03891bb.jpg?s=800&amp;c=85&amp;f=jpeg 800w, https://media.npr.org/assets/img/2024/03/11/ap24071617990627_wide-ea6040568f9ae3ac2cd3d8140014bf63d03891bb.jpg?s=900&amp;c=85&amp;f=jpeg 900w, https://media.npr.org/assets/img/2024/03/11/ap24071617990627_wide-ea6040568f9ae3ac2cd3d8140014bf63d03891bb.jpg?s=1200&amp;c=85&amp;f=jpeg 1200w, https://media.npr.org/assets/img/2024/03/11/ap24071617990627_wide-ea6040568f9ae3ac2cd3d8140014bf63d03891bb.jpg?s=1600&amp;c=85&amp;f=jpeg 1600w, https://media.npr.org/assets/img/2024/03/11/ap24071617990627_wide-ea6040568f9ae3ac2cd3d8140014bf63d03891bb.jpg?s=1800&amp;c=85&amp;f=jpeg 1800w" data-template="https://media.npr.org/assets/img/2024/03/11/ap24071617990627_wide-ea6040568f9ae3ac2cd3d8140014bf63d03891bb.jpg?s={width}&amp;c={quality}&amp;f={format}" sizes="(min-width: 1300px) 763px, (min-width: 1025px) calc(100vw - 496px), (min-width: 768px) calc(100vw - 171px), calc(100vw - 30px)" class="img" type="image/jpeg" /&gt;             &lt;img src="https://media.npr.org/assets/img/2024/03/11/ap24071617990627_wide-ea6040568f9ae3ac2cd3d8140014bf63d03891bb.jpg?s=1100&amp;c=50&amp;f=jpeg" data-template="https://media.npr.org/assets/img/2024/03/11/ap24071617990627_wide-ea6040568f9ae3ac2cd3d8140014bf63d03891bb.jpg?s={width}&amp;c={quality}&amp;f={format}" class="img" alt="The TikTok Inc. building is seen in Culver City, Calif., on March 17, 2023." loading="lazy" /&gt;         &lt;/picture&gt;          &lt;/div&gt; &lt;div class="credit-caption"&gt;     &lt;div class="caption-wrap"&gt;         &lt;div class="caption" aria-label="Image caption"&gt;             &lt;p&gt;                 The TikTok Inc. building is seen in Culver City, Calif., on March 17, 2023.                 &lt;b class="credit" aria-label="Image credit"&gt;                                          Damian Dovarganes/AP                                      &lt;/b&gt;                 &lt;b class="hide-caption"&gt;&lt;b&gt;&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/b&gt;             &lt;/p&gt;         &lt;/div&gt;               &lt;b class="toggle-caption"&gt;&lt;b&gt;&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/b&gt;     &lt;/div&gt;       &lt;/div&gt;      &lt;/div&gt;    &lt;ul class="edTag"&gt;&lt;li&gt;🎧 &lt;strong&gt;This is TikTok's last legal shot to not have to shut down in the U.S., unless it splits off from its Chinese parent company&lt;/strong&gt;, ByteDance, NPR's Bobby Allyn tells &lt;em&gt;Up First&lt;/em&gt;. The case is about the balance between &lt;a href="https://one.npr.org/?sharedMediaId=1220280840:1263782039" target="_blank"&gt;freedom of speech and the possible threat of a foreign adversary&lt;/a&gt;. TikTok has said the Chinese government doesn't collect data on Americans nor does it push propaganda, but U.S. officials said the risk remains too high. The Supreme Court has never taken on the case over the U.S. government attempting to shut down a massive social media platform, which makes this uncharted territory, Allyn says.&lt;/li&gt;&lt;/ul&gt;       &lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Republican lawmakers are working to avoid a government shutdown with less than a week until Christmas &lt;/strong&gt;after President-elect Donald Trump and allies spoke out against a bipartisan spending bill. Government funding runs out at the end of the day on Friday. Congressional leaders released a roughly 1,500-page bipartisan spending bill, which would fund the government until March 14 and covers priorities like farm subsidies, disaster aid and a pay raise for lawmakers. Yesterday, GOP leaders and Trump advisers &lt;a href="https://www.npr.org/2024/12/17/g-s1-38712/congress-spending-bill-march-14" target="_blank"&gt;pushed House Speaker Mike Johnson, R-La., to back out of the deal&lt;/a&gt;. House Democrats said they are unwilling to back away.&lt;/p&gt;   &lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Syrians and refugees on either side of the country's conflict can go home now that dictator Bashar al-Assad has been ousted.&lt;/strong&gt; The country is now accessible to journalists, allowing for a fuller look at it while in transition. &lt;br&gt;&lt;/p&gt;   &lt;ul class="edTag"&gt;&lt;li&gt;🎧 &lt;strong&gt;NPR's Jane Arraf, who is in Syria, says Damascus has drastically changed since the fall of the Assad regime. Arraf traveled&lt;/strong&gt; through Syria's southern desert to the Rukban camp — a place she's tried to travel to for years. People fleeing from ISIS thought they could cross through to Jordan there, but were trapped. For nine years, &lt;a href="https://one.npr.org/?sharedMediaId=1220280840:1263782039" target="_blank"&gt;7,000 people were cut off&lt;/a&gt;. For the first time, refugees in their own country have the opportunity to go home and reunite with their families.&lt;/li&gt;&lt;/ul&gt;       &lt;h3 class="edTag"&gt;Today's listen&lt;/h3&gt;   &lt;div id="resg-s1-38799" class="bucketwrap image large"&gt;             &lt;div     class="imagewrap has-source-dimensions"     data-crop-type=""     style="         --source-width: 3280;         --source-height: 1845;     " &gt;         &lt;picture&gt;             &lt;source srcset="https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/3280x1845+0+681/resize/400/quality/85/format/webp/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F78%2F74%2Fd16194ca4251b17f8e126df854b5%2Fgettyimages-460523824.jpg 400w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/3280x1845+0+681/resize/600/quality/85/format/webp/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F78%2F74%2Fd16194ca4251b17f8e126df854b5%2Fgettyimages-460523824.jpg 600w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/3280x1845+0+681/resize/800/quality/85/format/webp/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F78%2F74%2Fd16194ca4251b17f8e126df854b5%2Fgettyimages-460523824.jpg 800w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/3280x1845+0+681/resize/900/quality/85/format/webp/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F78%2F74%2Fd16194ca4251b17f8e126df854b5%2Fgettyimages-460523824.jpg 900w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/3280x1845+0+681/resize/1200/quality/85/format/webp/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F78%2F74%2Fd16194ca4251b17f8e126df854b5%2Fgettyimages-460523824.jpg 1200w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/3280x1845+0+681/resize/1600/quality/85/format/webp/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F78%2F74%2Fd16194ca4251b17f8e126df854b5%2Fgettyimages-460523824.jpg 1600w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/3280x1845+0+681/resize/1800/quality/85/format/webp/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F78%2F74%2Fd16194ca4251b17f8e126df854b5%2Fgettyimages-460523824.jpg 1800w" data-template="https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/3280x1845+0+681/resize/{width}/quality/{quality}/format/{format}/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F78%2F74%2Fd16194ca4251b17f8e126df854b5%2Fgettyimages-460523824.jpg" sizes="(min-width: 1300px) 763px, (min-width: 1025px) calc(100vw - 496px), (min-width: 768px) calc(100vw - 171px), calc(100vw - 30px)" class="img" type="image/webp" /&gt;             &lt;source srcset="https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/3280x1845+0+681/resize/400/quality/85/format/jpeg/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F78%2F74%2Fd16194ca4251b17f8e126df854b5%2Fgettyimages-460523824.jpg 400w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/3280x1845+0+681/resize/600/quality/85/format/jpeg/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F78%2F74%2Fd16194ca4251b17f8e126df854b5%2Fgettyimages-460523824.jpg 600w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/3280x1845+0+681/resize/800/quality/85/format/jpeg/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F78%2F74%2Fd16194ca4251b17f8e126df854b5%2Fgettyimages-460523824.jpg 800w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/3280x1845+0+681/resize/900/quality/85/format/jpeg/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F78%2F74%2Fd16194ca4251b17f8e126df854b5%2Fgettyimages-460523824.jpg 900w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/3280x1845+0+681/resize/1200/quality/85/format/jpeg/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F78%2F74%2Fd16194ca4251b17f8e126df854b5%2Fgettyimages-460523824.jpg 1200w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/3280x1845+0+681/resize/1600/quality/85/format/jpeg/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F78%2F74%2Fd16194ca4251b17f8e126df854b5%2Fgettyimages-460523824.jpg 1600w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/3280x1845+0+681/resize/1800/quality/85/format/jpeg/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F78%2F74%2Fd16194ca4251b17f8e126df854b5%2Fgettyimages-460523824.jpg 1800w" data-template="https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/3280x1845+0+681/resize/{width}/quality/{quality}/format/{format}/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F78%2F74%2Fd16194ca4251b17f8e126df854b5%2Fgettyimages-460523824.jpg" sizes="(min-width: 1300px) 763px, (min-width: 1025px) calc(100vw - 496px), (min-width: 768px) calc(100vw - 171px), calc(100vw - 30px)" class="img" type="image/jpeg" /&gt;             &lt;img src="https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/3280x1845+0+681/resize/1100/quality/50/format/jpeg/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F78%2F74%2Fd16194ca4251b17f8e126df854b5%2Fgettyimages-460523824.jpg" data-template="https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/3280x1845+0+681/resize/{width}/quality/{quality}/format/{format}/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F78%2F74%2Fd16194ca4251b17f8e126df854b5%2Fgettyimages-460523824.jpg" class="img" alt="Mariah Carey released &amp;quot;All I Want For Christmas Is You&amp;quot; in 1994, but it took 25 years for the song to reach the top of Billboard&amp;#039;s Hot 100 pop chart. Since 2019, it has topped the chart each December for a total of 16 weeks at No. 1 — so far." loading="lazy" /&gt;         &lt;/picture&gt; &lt;/div&gt; &lt;div class="credit-caption"&gt;     &lt;div class="caption-wrap"&gt;         &lt;div class="caption" aria-label="Image caption"&gt;             &lt;p&gt;                 Mariah Carey released "All I Want For Christmas Is You" in 1994, but it took 25 years for the song to reach the top of &lt;em&gt;Billboard&lt;/em&gt;'s Hot 100 pop chart. Since 2019, it has topped the chart each December for a total of 16 weeks at No. 1 — so far.                 &lt;b class="credit" aria-label="Image credit"&gt;                                          Dimitrios Kambouris/Getty Images                                      &lt;/b&gt;                 &lt;b class="hide-caption"&gt;&lt;b&gt;&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/b&gt;             &lt;/p&gt;         &lt;/div&gt;               &lt;b class="toggle-caption"&gt;&lt;b&gt;&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/b&gt;     &lt;/div&gt;       &lt;/div&gt;    &lt;/div&gt;    &lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;It's the time of year when familiar Christmas songs take over the top spots on the Billboard pop chart.&lt;/strong&gt; The annual invasion features the current top five songs from the 1950s and '60s. When the No. 1 song, Mariah Carey's "All I Want for Christmas Is You," was released in 1994 it didn't take the top spot. That happened 25 years later. The top five songs this week are predictable year after year, but a few newer songs are making a play to join in on the annual holiday playlist. Learn what changed since those songs were released and &lt;a href="https://one.npr.org/?sharedMediaId=nx-s1-5230470:nx-s1-5297511-1" target="_blank"&gt;listen to some of the holiday music vying&lt;/a&gt; for top spots.&lt;br&gt;&lt;/p&gt;   &lt;h3 class="edTag"&gt;Life advice&lt;/h3&gt;   &lt;div id="resg-s1-39023" class="bucketwrap image large"&gt;             &lt;div     class="imagewrap has-source-dimensions"     data-crop-type=""     style="         --source-width: 600;         --source-height: 337;     " &gt;         &lt;picture&gt;             &lt;source srcset="https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/600x337+0+0/resize/400/quality/85/format/webp/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fa5%2F2e%2Fda0f09dd443fa1ec74dcd6a73682%2Fnpr-sad-capossela-wide-1e73317da9c61b7256c7a2cf1fef71f7e4e5da02.jpg 400w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/600x337+0+0/resize/600/quality/85/format/webp/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fa5%2F2e%2Fda0f09dd443fa1ec74dcd6a73682%2Fnpr-sad-capossela-wide-1e73317da9c61b7256c7a2cf1fef71f7e4e5da02.jpg 600w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/600x337+0+0/resize/800/quality/85/format/webp/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fa5%2F2e%2Fda0f09dd443fa1ec74dcd6a73682%2Fnpr-sad-capossela-wide-1e73317da9c61b7256c7a2cf1fef71f7e4e5da02.jpg 800w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/600x337+0+0/resize/900/quality/85/format/webp/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fa5%2F2e%2Fda0f09dd443fa1ec74dcd6a73682%2Fnpr-sad-capossela-wide-1e73317da9c61b7256c7a2cf1fef71f7e4e5da02.jpg 900w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/600x337+0+0/resize/1200/quality/85/format/webp/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fa5%2F2e%2Fda0f09dd443fa1ec74dcd6a73682%2Fnpr-sad-capossela-wide-1e73317da9c61b7256c7a2cf1fef71f7e4e5da02.jpg 1200w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/600x337+0+0/resize/1600/quality/85/format/webp/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fa5%2F2e%2Fda0f09dd443fa1ec74dcd6a73682%2Fnpr-sad-capossela-wide-1e73317da9c61b7256c7a2cf1fef71f7e4e5da02.jpg 1600w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/600x337+0+0/resize/1800/quality/85/format/webp/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fa5%2F2e%2Fda0f09dd443fa1ec74dcd6a73682%2Fnpr-sad-capossela-wide-1e73317da9c61b7256c7a2cf1fef71f7e4e5da02.jpg 1800w" data-template="https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/600x337+0+0/resize/{width}/quality/{quality}/format/{format}/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fa5%2F2e%2Fda0f09dd443fa1ec74dcd6a73682%2Fnpr-sad-capossela-wide-1e73317da9c61b7256c7a2cf1fef71f7e4e5da02.jpg" sizes="(min-width: 1300px) 763px, (min-width: 1025px) calc(100vw - 496px), (min-width: 768px) calc(100vw - 171px), calc(100vw - 30px)" class="img" type="image/webp" /&gt;             &lt;source srcset="https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/600x337+0+0/resize/400/quality/85/format/jpeg/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fa5%2F2e%2Fda0f09dd443fa1ec74dcd6a73682%2Fnpr-sad-capossela-wide-1e73317da9c61b7256c7a2cf1fef71f7e4e5da02.jpg 400w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/600x337+0+0/resize/600/quality/85/format/jpeg/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fa5%2F2e%2Fda0f09dd443fa1ec74dcd6a73682%2Fnpr-sad-capossela-wide-1e73317da9c61b7256c7a2cf1fef71f7e4e5da02.jpg 600w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/600x337+0+0/resize/800/quality/85/format/jpeg/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fa5%2F2e%2Fda0f09dd443fa1ec74dcd6a73682%2Fnpr-sad-capossela-wide-1e73317da9c61b7256c7a2cf1fef71f7e4e5da02.jpg 800w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/600x337+0+0/resize/900/quality/85/format/jpeg/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fa5%2F2e%2Fda0f09dd443fa1ec74dcd6a73682%2Fnpr-sad-capossela-wide-1e73317da9c61b7256c7a2cf1fef71f7e4e5da02.jpg 900w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/600x337+0+0/resize/1200/quality/85/format/jpeg/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fa5%2F2e%2Fda0f09dd443fa1ec74dcd6a73682%2Fnpr-sad-capossela-wide-1e73317da9c61b7256c7a2cf1fef71f7e4e5da02.jpg 1200w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/600x337+0+0/resize/1600/quality/85/format/jpeg/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fa5%2F2e%2Fda0f09dd443fa1ec74dcd6a73682%2Fnpr-sad-capossela-wide-1e73317da9c61b7256c7a2cf1fef71f7e4e5da02.jpg 1600w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/600x337+0+0/resize/1800/quality/85/format/jpeg/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fa5%2F2e%2Fda0f09dd443fa1ec74dcd6a73682%2Fnpr-sad-capossela-wide-1e73317da9c61b7256c7a2cf1fef71f7e4e5da02.jpg 1800w" data-template="https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/600x337+0+0/resize/{width}/quality/{quality}/format/{format}/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fa5%2F2e%2Fda0f09dd443fa1ec74dcd6a73682%2Fnpr-sad-capossela-wide-1e73317da9c61b7256c7a2cf1fef71f7e4e5da02.jpg" sizes="(min-width: 1300px) 763px, (min-width: 1025px) calc(100vw - 496px), (min-width: 768px) calc(100vw - 171px), calc(100vw - 30px)" class="img" type="image/jpeg" /&gt;             &lt;img src="https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/600x337+0+0/resize/1100/quality/50/format/jpeg/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fa5%2F2e%2Fda0f09dd443fa1ec74dcd6a73682%2Fnpr-sad-capossela-wide-1e73317da9c61b7256c7a2cf1fef71f7e4e5da02.jpg" data-template="https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/600x337+0+0/resize/{width}/quality/{quality}/format/{format}/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fa5%2F2e%2Fda0f09dd443fa1ec74dcd6a73682%2Fnpr-sad-capossela-wide-1e73317da9c61b7256c7a2cf1fef71f7e4e5da02.jpg" class="img" alt="npr-sad-capossela_wide-1e73317da9c61b7256c7a2cf1fef71f7e4e5da02.jpg" loading="lazy" /&gt;         &lt;/picture&gt; &lt;/div&gt; &lt;div class="credit-caption"&gt;     &lt;div class="caption-wrap"&gt;         &lt;div class="caption" aria-label="Image caption"&gt;         &lt;/div&gt;       &lt;/div&gt;       &lt;/div&gt;    &lt;/div&gt;    &lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;As days get darker and colder, people may experience seasonal affective disorder, or SAD.&lt;/strong&gt; As the seasons change, you may feel sluggish, depressed or uninterested in doing the things you used to enjoy. You may also oversleep or overeat. Around 1 in 20 people in the U.S. has SAD. Many more people have the winter blues, a milder version of SAD, where you feel like a sadder, sleepier or slower version of yourself. &lt;a href="https://www.npr.org/2020/10/23/927135639/coping-with-sad-or-seasonal-affective-disorder" target="_blank"&gt;Here's how to spot it&lt;/a&gt; and what you can do. &lt;br&gt;&lt;/p&gt;   &lt;ul class="edTag"&gt;&lt;li&gt;❄️ &lt;strong&gt;It can be hard to recognize a pattern of change because symptoms can creep up on you&lt;/strong&gt;, says Dr. Norman Rosenthal, a clinical professor of psychiatry at Georgetown University School of Medicine.&lt;/li&gt;&lt;li&gt;❄️ &lt;strong&gt;Not getting enough light is at the heart of the disorder. &lt;/strong&gt;A SAD lamp, which provides more intense light than indoor lighting, is often recommended.&lt;/li&gt;&lt;li&gt;❄️&lt;strong&gt; Make time for movement. &lt;/strong&gt;You may feel less energetic when the seasons change, and that can turn into a vicious cycle. Exercise is an environmental cue that helps signal your internal clock.&lt;/li&gt;&lt;/ul&gt;   &lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Here's more &lt;/strong&gt;on &lt;a href="https://www.npr.org/2020/10/23/927135639/coping-with-sad-or-seasonal-affective-disorder" target="_blank"&gt;why you may feel this way&lt;/a&gt; and ways to feel better.&lt;/p&gt;   &lt;h3 class="edTag"&gt;3 things to know before you go&lt;/h3&gt;   &lt;div id="resg-s1-39015" class="bucketwrap image large"&gt;             &lt;div     class="imagewrap has-source-dimensions"     data-crop-type=""     style="         --source-width: 3500;         --source-height: 1969;     " &gt;         &lt;picture&gt;             &lt;source srcset="https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/3500x1969+0+0/resize/400/quality/85/format/webp/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F03%2Ffb%2F5970d114483f897ad3461220f83c%2Fap24172044351851.jpg 400w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/3500x1969+0+0/resize/600/quality/85/format/webp/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F03%2Ffb%2F5970d114483f897ad3461220f83c%2Fap24172044351851.jpg 600w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/3500x1969+0+0/resize/800/quality/85/format/webp/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F03%2Ffb%2F5970d114483f897ad3461220f83c%2Fap24172044351851.jpg 800w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/3500x1969+0+0/resize/900/quality/85/format/webp/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F03%2Ffb%2F5970d114483f897ad3461220f83c%2Fap24172044351851.jpg 900w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/3500x1969+0+0/resize/1200/quality/85/format/webp/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F03%2Ffb%2F5970d114483f897ad3461220f83c%2Fap24172044351851.jpg 1200w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/3500x1969+0+0/resize/1600/quality/85/format/webp/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F03%2Ffb%2F5970d114483f897ad3461220f83c%2Fap24172044351851.jpg 1600w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/3500x1969+0+0/resize/1800/quality/85/format/webp/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F03%2Ffb%2F5970d114483f897ad3461220f83c%2Fap24172044351851.jpg 1800w" data-template="https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/3500x1969+0+0/resize/{width}/quality/{quality}/format/{format}/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F03%2Ffb%2F5970d114483f897ad3461220f83c%2Fap24172044351851.jpg" sizes="(min-width: 1300px) 763px, (min-width: 1025px) calc(100vw - 496px), (min-width: 768px) calc(100vw - 171px), calc(100vw - 30px)" class="img" type="image/webp" /&gt;             &lt;source srcset="https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/3500x1969+0+0/resize/400/quality/85/format/jpeg/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F03%2Ffb%2F5970d114483f897ad3461220f83c%2Fap24172044351851.jpg 400w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/3500x1969+0+0/resize/600/quality/85/format/jpeg/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F03%2Ffb%2F5970d114483f897ad3461220f83c%2Fap24172044351851.jpg 600w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/3500x1969+0+0/resize/800/quality/85/format/jpeg/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F03%2Ffb%2F5970d114483f897ad3461220f83c%2Fap24172044351851.jpg 800w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/3500x1969+0+0/resize/900/quality/85/format/jpeg/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F03%2Ffb%2F5970d114483f897ad3461220f83c%2Fap24172044351851.jpg 900w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/3500x1969+0+0/resize/1200/quality/85/format/jpeg/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F03%2Ffb%2F5970d114483f897ad3461220f83c%2Fap24172044351851.jpg 1200w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/3500x1969+0+0/resize/1600/quality/85/format/jpeg/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F03%2Ffb%2F5970d114483f897ad3461220f83c%2Fap24172044351851.jpg 1600w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/3500x1969+0+0/resize/1800/quality/85/format/jpeg/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F03%2Ffb%2F5970d114483f897ad3461220f83c%2Fap24172044351851.jpg 1800w" data-template="https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/3500x1969+0+0/resize/{width}/quality/{quality}/format/{format}/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F03%2Ffb%2F5970d114483f897ad3461220f83c%2Fap24172044351851.jpg" sizes="(min-width: 1300px) 763px, (min-width: 1025px) calc(100vw - 496px), (min-width: 768px) calc(100vw - 171px), calc(100vw - 30px)" class="img" type="image/jpeg" /&gt;             &lt;img src="https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/3500x1969+0+0/resize/1100/quality/50/format/jpeg/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F03%2Ffb%2F5970d114483f897ad3461220f83c%2Fap24172044351851.jpg" data-template="https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/3500x1969+0+0/resize/{width}/quality/{quality}/format/{format}/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F03%2Ffb%2F5970d114483f897ad3461220f83c%2Fap24172044351851.jpg" class="img" alt="Teamsters General President Sean M. O&amp;#039;Brien, center, rallies with Amazon workers outside the Staten Island Amazon facility JFK8 on Wednesday, June 19, 2024 in New York." loading="lazy" /&gt;         &lt;/picture&gt; &lt;/div&gt; &lt;div class="credit-caption"&gt;     &lt;div class="caption-wrap"&gt;         &lt;div class="caption" aria-label="Image caption"&gt;             &lt;p&gt;                 Teamsters General President Sean M. O'Brien, center, rallies with Amazon workers outside the Staten Island Amazon facility JFK8 on Wednesday, June 19, 2024 in New York.                 &lt;b class="credit" aria-label="Image credit"&gt;                                          Stefan Jeremiah/AP                                      &lt;/b&gt;                 &lt;b class="hide-caption"&gt;&lt;b&gt;&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/b&gt;             &lt;/p&gt;         &lt;/div&gt;               &lt;b class="toggle-caption"&gt;&lt;b&gt;&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/b&gt;     &lt;/div&gt;       &lt;/div&gt;    &lt;/div&gt;    &lt;ol class="edTag"&gt;&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Thousands of Amazon workers have authorized a strike to begin this morning&lt;/strong&gt;, during a key shopping period, as they seek &lt;a href="https://www.npr.org/2024/12/19/nx-s1-5233832/amazon-strike" target="_blank"&gt;better pay, safer conditions and longer breaks&lt;/a&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;This week, the House of Representatives passed a bill to officially designate the bald eagle&lt;/strong&gt;, a symbol of the United States for centuries, as &lt;a href="https://www.npr.org/2024/12/18/nx-s1-5231827/bald-eagles-national-bird" target="_blank"&gt;the country's national bird&lt;/a&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Have you ever been caught red-handed regifting during the holidays?&lt;/strong&gt; If the answer is yes, &lt;a href="https://www.npr.org/2024/12/17/g-s1-38636/embarrassing-regifting-story" target="_blank"&gt;NPR wants to hear your stories&lt;/a&gt;. The more embarrassing they are, the better.&lt;/li&gt;&lt;/ol&gt;       &lt;p&gt;&lt;em&gt;This newsletter was edited by &lt;/em&gt;&lt;a href="https://www.npr.org/people/859721331/suzanne-nuyen"target="_blank"   &gt;&lt;em&gt;Suzanne Nuyen&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;em&gt;.&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;/div&gt;</description>
