sc1920-edit.jpg" sizes="(min-width: 1300px) 763px, (min-width: 1025px) calc(100vw - 496px), (min-width: 768px) calc(100vw - 171px), calc(100vw - 30px)" class="img" type="image/webp" /&gt;             &lt;source srcset="https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/2925x1645+0+152/resize/400/quality/85/format/jpeg/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F41%2Faf%2Fd9f502da41739763f8b95c0fb896%2F20241212-dsc1920-edit.jpg 400w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/2925x1645+0+152/resize/600/quality/85/format/jpeg/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F41%2Faf%2Fd9f502da41739763f8b95c0fb896%2F20241212-dsc1920-edit.jpg 600w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/2925x1645+0+152/resize/800/quality/85/format/jpeg/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F41%2Faf%2Fd9f502da41739763f8b95c0fb896%2F20241212-dsc1920-edit.jpg 800w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/2925x1645+0+152/resize/900/quality/85/format/jpeg/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F41%2Faf%2Fd9f502da41739763f8b95c0fb896%2F20241212-dsc1920-edit.jpg 900w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/2925x1645+0+152/resize/1200/quality/85/format/jpeg/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F41%2Faf%2Fd9f502da41739763f8b95c0fb896%2F20241212-dsc1920-edit.jpg 1200w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/2925x1645+0+152/resize/1600/quality/85/format/jpeg/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F41%2Faf%2Fd9f502da41739763f8b95c0fb896%2F20241212-dsc1920-edit.jpg 1600w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/2925x1645+0+152/resize/1800/quality/85/format/jpeg/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F41%2Faf%2Fd9f502da41739763f8b95c0fb896%2F20241212-dsc1920-edit.jpg 1800w" data-template="https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/2925x1645+0+152/resize/{width}/quality/{quality}/format/{format}/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F41%2Faf%2Fd9f502da41739763f8b95c0fb896%2F20241212-dsc1920-edit.jpg" sizes="(min-width: 1300px) 763px, (min-width: 1025px) calc(100vw - 496px), (min-width: 768px) calc(100vw - 171px), calc(100vw - 30px)" class="img" type="image/jpeg" /&gt;             &lt;img src="https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/2925x1645+0+152/resize/1100/quality/50/format/jpeg/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F41%2Faf%2Fd9f502da41739763f8b95c0fb896%2F20241212-dsc1920-edit.jpg" data-template="https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/2925x1645+0+152/resize/{width}/quality/{quality}/format/{format}/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F41%2Faf%2Fd9f502da41739763f8b95c0fb896%2F20241212-dsc1920-edit.jpg" class="img" alt="" loading="lazy" /&gt;         &lt;/picture&gt; &lt;/div&gt; &lt;div class="credit-caption"&gt;     &lt;div class="caption-wrap"&gt;         &lt;div class="caption" aria-label="Image caption"&gt;             &lt;p&gt;                 Sarah Abdel Hamid al-Aami is searching for her four brothers who were snatched on their way to work by government forces years ago on what she says were bogus accusations of terrorism.                 &lt;b class="credit" aria-label="Image credit"&gt;                                          Clare Harbage/NPR                                      &lt;/b&gt;                 &lt;b class="hide-caption"&gt;&lt;b&gt;&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/b&gt;             &lt;/p&gt;         &lt;/div&gt;               &lt;b class="toggle-caption"&gt;&lt;b&gt;&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/b&gt;     &lt;/div&gt;       &lt;/div&gt;    &lt;/div&gt;    &lt;p&gt;&lt;em&gt;This essay was written by Morning Edition senior editor and reporter Arezou Rezvani.  Rezvani and a team from &lt;/em&gt;&lt;br&gt;&lt;em&gt;Morning Edition are on the ground in Syria, covering the fall of Bashar al-Assad's regime. &lt;/em&gt;&lt;/p&gt;   &lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;For decades, Syrians have lived in a constant state of fear and paranoia.&lt;/strong&gt; For 54 years, under the rule of dictator Bashar al-Assad and his father before him, there was no tolerance for criticizing the government. Those who did speak out often disappeared into Syria's notorious prison system, known for soul-crushing torture and killings. The oppression took an even darker turn in 2011 after Assad's regime crushed pro-democracy protests and clamped down on any association with emerging opposition groups. During the ensuing 13-year civil war, friends, neighbors and colleagues would avoid political discussions. Even in the privacy of their own homes, Syrians remained tight-lipped. Parents withheld their true feelings from their own children for fear they'd say something at school, where they were closely monitored by teachers and staff who would report on families if they sensed any hints of disloyalty at home. It was commonly said that in Syria, "the walls have ears."&lt;/p&gt;       &lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;With Bashar al-Assad now gone, Syrians are slowly starting to come out and share their secrets.&lt;/strong&gt; Long-time friends are &lt;a href="https://www.npr.org/2024/12/12/nx-s1-5225551/on-the-road-from-beirut-to-damascus-people-find-their-footing-in-a-new-syria"&gt;&lt;u&gt;revealing details about their lives they had long kept under wraps&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/a&gt;, like their imprisonments, the rebel-held cities their families are originally from, their religions, political leanings, dreams, aspirations, unfiltered thoughts and ideas. After so many decades of repression, many Syrians say this newfound freedom to speak doesn't come naturally, that it's almost like they need to be deprogrammed.&lt;/p&gt;   &lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Lurking underneath the thrill of the moment is a great deal of anxiety. &lt;/strong&gt;There are still a lot of questions about the rebel groups that toppled Assad. Will they accept criticism? Will they hold free and fair elections? Will all religious and minority groups be protected? Have they really abandoned all links with al-Qaeda and the Islamic State? Syrians are celebrating the end of Assad rule, &lt;a href="https://www.npr.org/2024/12/12/nx-s1-5225551/on-the-road-from-beirut-to-damascus-people-find-their-footing-in-a-new-syria"&gt;&lt;u&gt;but they're holding their breath&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/a&gt; for what's to come.&lt;br&gt;&lt;/p&gt;   &lt;h3 class="edTag"&gt;Life advice&lt;/h3&gt;   &lt;div id="resg-s1-38127" class="bucketwrap image large"&gt;             &lt;div     class="imagewrap has-source-dimensions"     data-crop-type=""     style="         --source-width: 4256;         --source-height: 2394;     " &gt;         &lt;picture&gt;             &lt;source srcset="https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/4256x2394+0+219/resize/400/quality/85/format/webp/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F18%2F90%2F93cd1e91404a9bf045b63fd74bec%2Fgettyimages-1242117123.jpg 400w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/4256x2394+0+219/resize/600/quality/85/format/webp/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F18%2F90%2F93cd1e91404a9bf045b63fd74bec%2Fgettyimages-1242117123.jpg 600w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/4256x2394+0+219/resize/800/quality/85/format/webp/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F18%2F90%2F93cd1e91404a9bf045b63fd74bec%2Fgettyimages-1242117123.jpg 800w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/4256x2394+0+219/resize/900/quality/85/format/webp/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F18%2F90%2F93cd1e91404a9bf045b63fd74bec%2Fgettyimages-1242117123.jpg 900w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/4256x2394+0+219/resize/1200/quality/85/format/webp/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F18%2F90%2F93cd1e91404a9bf045b63fd74bec%2Fgettyimages-1242117123.jpg 1200w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/4256x2394+0+219/resize/1600/quality/85/format/webp/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F18%2F90%2F93cd1e91404a9bf045b63fd74bec%2Fgettyimages-1242117123.jpg 1600w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/4256x2394+0+219/resize/1800/quality/85/format/webp/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F18%2F90%2F93cd1e91404a9bf045b63fd74bec%2Fgettyimages-1242117123.jpg 1800w" data-template="https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/4256x2394+0+219/resize/{width}/quality/{quality}/format/{format}/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F18%2F90%2F93cd1e91404a9bf045b63fd74bec%2Fgettyimages-1242117123.jpg" sizes="(min-width: 1300px) 763px, (min-width: 1025px) calc(100vw - 496px), (min-width: 768px) calc(100vw - 171px), calc(100vw - 30px)" class="img" type="image/webp" /&gt;             &lt;source srcset="https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/4256x2394+0+219/resize/400/quality/85/format/jpeg/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F18%2F90%2F93cd1e91404a9bf045b63fd74bec%2Fgettyimages-1242117123.jpg 400w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/4256x2394+0+219/resize/600/quality/85/format/jpeg/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F18%2F90%2F93cd1e91404a9bf045b63fd74bec%2Fgettyimages-1242117123.jpg 600w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/4256x2394+0+219/resize/800/quality/85/format/jpeg/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F18%2F90%2F93cd1e91404a9bf045b63fd74bec%2Fgettyimages-1242117123.jpg 800w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/4256x2394+0+219/resize/900/quality/85/format/jpeg/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F18%2F90%2F93cd1e91404a9bf045b63fd74bec%2Fgettyimages-1242117123.jpg 900w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/4256x2394+0+219/resize/1200/quality/85/format/jpeg/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F18%2F90%2F93cd1e91404a9bf045b63fd74bec%2Fgettyimages-1242117123.jpg 1200w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/4256x2394+0+219/resize/1600/quality/85/format/jpeg/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F18%2F90%2F93cd1e91404a9bf045b63fd74bec%2Fgettyimages-1242117123.jpg 1600w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/4256x2394+0+219/resize/1800/quality/85/format/jpeg/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F18%2F90%2F93cd1e91404a9bf045b63fd74bec%2Fgettyimages-1242117123.jpg 1800w" data-template="https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/4256x2394+0+219/resize/{width}/quality/{quality}/format/{format}/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F18%2F90%2F93cd1e91404a9bf045b63fd74bec%2Fgettyimages-1242117123.jpg" sizes="(min-width: 1300px) 763px, (min-width: 1025px) calc(100vw - 496px), (min-width: 768px) calc(100vw - 171px), calc(100vw - 30px)" class="img" type="image/jpeg" /&gt;             &lt;img src="https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/4256x2394+0+219/resize/1100/quality/50/format/jpeg/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F18%2F90%2F93cd1e91404a9bf045b63fd74bec%2Fgettyimages-1242117123.jpg" data-template="https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/4256x2394+0+219/resize/{width}/quality/{quality}/format/{format}/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F18%2F90%2F93cd1e91404a9bf045b63fd74bec%2Fgettyimages-1242117123.jpg" class="img" alt="A father teaches his child to swim in a pond in Sylhet, Bangladesh." loading="lazy" /&gt;         &lt;/picture&gt; &lt;/div&gt; &lt;div class="credit-caption"&gt;     &lt;div class="caption-wrap"&gt;         &lt;div class="caption" aria-label="Image caption"&gt;             &lt;p&gt;                 A father teaches his child to swim in a pond in Sylhet, Bangladesh. Drowning is a leading causes of death globally for children, according to the first ever report on drowning as a public health issue issued by the World Health Organization.                 &lt;b class="credit" aria-label="Image credit"&gt;                                          Md Rafayat Haque Khan/Eyepix Group/Future Publishing via Getty Images                                      &lt;/b&gt;                 &lt;b class="hide-caption"&gt;&lt;b&gt;&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/b&gt;             &lt;/p&gt;         &lt;/div&gt;               &lt;b class="toggle-caption"&gt;&lt;b&gt;&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/b&gt;     &lt;/div&gt;       &lt;/div&gt;    &lt;/div&gt;    &lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;More than 300,000 people die from drowning each year. &lt;/strong&gt;A new World Health Organization report found that nearly all cases are preventable. WHO gathered data from 139 countries for its first-ever report on how to prevent drowning. Children are the highest-risk group, with nearly a quarter of all drowning deaths happening among kids under age 4. The threat is evolving as climate change makes floods more frequent and severe. Caroline Lukaszyk, a technical officer for injury prevention at the WHO, &lt;a href="https://www.npr.org/sections/goats-and-soda/2024/12/13/g-s1-38078/drowning-swimming-public-health-who"&gt;share some findings with NPR&lt;/a&gt;. &lt;br&gt;&lt;/p&gt;   &lt;ul class="edTag"&gt;&lt;li&gt;🌊&lt;strong&gt; A lot of the drowning burden is in Southeast Asia and Africa. &lt;/strong&gt;There are bodies of water everywhere throughout the communities, and people need them for drinking, cooking, washing and bathing. But they pose a risk for unsupervised youth.&lt;/li&gt;&lt;li&gt;🌊 &lt;strong&gt;It's good to have life jackets on board boats.&lt;/strong&gt; There's work being done to use local materials, such as empty two-liter plastic bottles, as flotation devices.&lt;/li&gt;&lt;li&gt;🌊 &lt;strong&gt;Swimming lessons that teach water safety&lt;/strong&gt; and survival skills can be low-cost solutions.&lt;/li&gt;&lt;li&gt;🌊 &lt;strong&gt;Bystander training and safe rescue and resuscitation are also recommended.&lt;/strong&gt; It can be key to teach CPR to older children and adults who could be around children playing in bodies of water.&lt;/li&gt;&lt;/ul&gt;       &lt;h3 class="edTag"&gt;3 things to know before you go&lt;/h3&gt;   &lt;div id="resg-s1-38346" class="bucketwrap image large"&gt;             &lt;div     class="imagewrap has-source-dimensions"     data-crop-type=""     style="         --source-width: 4080;         --source-height: 2295;     " &gt;         &lt;picture&gt;             &lt;source srcset="https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/4080x2295+0+389/resize/400/quality/85/format/webp/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fb8%2Fc1%2F67a071984beba9098453887ba1e8%2Fcaroline-davis.JPG 400w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/4080x2295+0+389/resize/600/quality/85/format/webp/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fb8%2Fc1%2F67a071984beba9098453887ba1e8%2Fcaroline-davis.JPG 600w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/4080x2295+0+389/resize/800/quality/85/format/webp/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fb8%2Fc1%2F67a071984beba9098453887ba1e8%2Fcaroline-davis.JPG 800w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/4080x2295+0+389/resize/900/quality/85/format/webp/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fb8%2Fc1%2F67a071984beba9098453887ba1e8%2Fcaroline-davis.JPG 900w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/4080x2295+0+389/resize/1200/quality/85/format/webp/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fb8%2Fc1%2F67a071984beba9098453887ba1e8%2Fcaroline-davis.JPG 1200w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/4080x2295+0+389/resize/1600/quality/85/format/webp/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fb8%2Fc1%2F67a071984beba9098453887ba1e8%2Fcaroline-davis.JPG 1600w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/4080x2295+0+389/resize/1800/quality/85/format/webp/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fb8%2Fc1%2F67a071984beba9098453887ba1e8%2Fcaroline-davis.JPG 1800w" data-template="https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/4080x2295+0+389/resize/{width}/quality/{quality}/format/{format}/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fb8%2Fc1%2F67a071984beba9098453887ba1e8%2Fcaroline-davis.JPG" sizes="(min-width: 1300px) 763px, (min-width: 1025px) calc(100vw - 496px), (min-width: 768px) calc(100vw - 171px), calc(100vw - 30px)" class="img" type="image/webp" /&gt;             &lt;source srcset="https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/4080x2295+0+389/resize/400/quality/85/format/jpeg/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fb8%2Fc1%2F67a071984beba9098453887ba1e8%2Fcaroline-davis.JPG 400w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/4080x2295+0+389/resize/600/quality/85/format/jpeg/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fb8%2Fc1%2F67a071984beba9098453887ba1e8%2Fcaroline-davis.JPG 600w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/4080x2295+0+389/resize/800/quality/85/format/jpeg/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fb8%2Fc1%2F67a071984beba9098453887ba1e8%2Fcaroline-davis.JPG 800w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/4080x2295+0+389/resize/900/quality/85/format/jpeg/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fb8%2Fc1%2F67a071984beba9098453887ba1e8%2Fcaroline-davis.JPG 900w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/4080x2295+0+389/resize/1200/quality/85/format/jpeg/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fb8%2Fc1%2F67a071984beba9098453887ba1e8%2Fcaroline-davis.JPG 1200w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/4080x2295+0+389/resize/1600/quality/85/format/jpeg/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fb8%2Fc1%2F67a071984beba9098453887ba1e8%2Fcaroline-davis.JPG 1600w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/4080x2295+0+389/resize/1800/quality/85/format/jpeg/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fb8%2Fc1%2F67a071984beba9098453887ba1e8%2Fcaroline-davis.JPG 1800w" data-template="https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/4080x2295+0+389/resize/{width}/quality/{quality}/format/{format}/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fb8%2Fc1%2F67a071984beba9098453887ba1e8%2Fcaroline-davis.JPG" sizes="(min-width: 1300px) 763px, (min-width: 1025px) calc(100vw - 496px), (min-width: 768px) calc(100vw - 171px), calc(100vw - 30px)" class="img" type="image/jpeg" /&gt;             &lt;img src="https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/4080x2295+0+389/resize/1100/quality/50/format/jpeg/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fb8%2Fc1%2F67a071984beba9098453887ba1e8%2Fcaroline-davis.JPG" data-template="https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/4080x2295+0+389/resize/{width}/quality/{quality}/format/{format}/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fb8%2Fc1%2F67a071984beba9098453887ba1e8%2Fcaroline-davis.JPG" class="img" alt="Caroline Davis said a stranger&amp;#039;s generosity reminder her of her dad." loading="lazy" /&gt;         &lt;/picture&gt; &lt;/div&gt; &lt;div class="credit-caption"&gt;     &lt;div class="caption-wrap"&gt;         &lt;div class="caption" aria-label="Image caption"&gt;             &lt;p&gt;                 Caroline Davis said a stranger's generosity reminder her of her dad.                 &lt;b class="credit" aria-label="Image credit"&gt;                                          Caroline David                                      &lt;/b&gt;                 &lt;b class="hide-caption"&gt;&lt;b&gt;&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/b&gt;             &lt;/p&gt;         &lt;/div&gt;               &lt;b class="toggle-caption"&gt;&lt;b&gt;&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/b&gt;     &lt;/div&gt;       &lt;/div&gt;    &lt;/div&gt;    &lt;ol class="edTag"&gt;&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;This past summer, Caroline Davis was working on a DIY project that required 1,500 pounds of gravel. &lt;/strong&gt;As she loaded her car with 50-pound bags, a stranger &lt;a href="https://www.npr.org/2024/12/14/g-s1-38341/unsung-hero-strangers-generosity-reminded-her-of-dad"&gt;stepped in and warned her&lt;/a&gt; of the damage it could cause to the vehicle. The unsung hero then helped her with the load. The interaction reminded her of her dad, who died in 2017.&lt;/li&gt;&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Indian tabla player Zakir Hussain, whose career spanned over five decades&lt;/strong&gt;, &lt;a href="https://www.npr.org/2024/12/15/nx-s1-5229593/zakir-hussain-dead-india-shakti-tabla"&gt;died yesterday at age 73&lt;/a&gt;. Hussain is revered as a national treasure.&lt;/li&gt;&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Two men were arrested Saturday for allegedly flying a drone &lt;/strong&gt;&lt;a href="https://www.npr.org/2024/12/16/nx-s1-5230075/drone-boston-logan-airport"&gt;"dangerously close" to Logan International Airport&lt;/a&gt;, the Boston Police Department said. The arrests come as drones have been sighted across the East Coast.&lt;/li&gt;&lt;/ol&gt;   &lt;p&gt;&lt;em&gt;This newsletter was edited by &lt;/em&gt;&lt;a href="https://www.npr.org/people/859721331/suzanne-nuyen"&gt;&lt;em&gt;Suzanne Nuyen&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;em&gt;.&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;/div&gt;</description>
