      <title>Foreign students advised to make plans before Trump. And, 2024's final news quiz</title>
      <author>Brittney Melton</author>
      <link>https://www.npr.org/2024/12/13/g-s1-38068/up-first-newsletter-international-university-students-holiday-travel-donald-trump-iran-syria</link>
      <comments>https://text.npr.org/2024/12/13/g-s1-38068/up-first-newsletter-international-university-students-holiday-travel-donald-trump-iran-syria</comments>
      <guid isPermaLink="true">https://www.npr.org/2024/12/13/g-s1-38068/up-first-newsletter-international-university-students-holiday-travel-donald-trump-iran-syria</guid>
      <pubDate>Fri, 13 Dec 2024 13:03:05 +0000</pubDate>
      <description>&lt;div id="storytext" class="storytext storylocation linkLocation"&gt;       &lt;p&gt;&lt;em&gt;Good morning. You're reading the Up First newsletter. &lt;/em&gt;&lt;a href="https://www.npr.org/newsletter/news"&gt;Subscribe&lt;/a&gt;&lt;em&gt; here to get it delivered to your inbox, and &lt;/em&gt;&lt;a href="https://www.npr.org/podcasts/510318/up-first/"&gt;listen&lt;/a&gt;&lt;em&gt; to the Up First podcast for all the news you need to start your day.&lt;/em&gt;&lt;br&gt;&lt;/p&gt;   &lt;h3 class="edTag"&gt;Today's top stories&lt;/h3&gt;   &lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Iran's capital has been in dismay after the sudden collapse of the Syrian regime. &lt;/strong&gt;Iran, a longtime enemy of Israel and the U.S., relied on Syria as one of its biggest allies in a bid for power across the Middle East. Iran propped up Syria's now-ousted ruler, Bashar al-Assad. Syria offered a connection to Iran's proxies in nearby Lebanon.&lt;/p&gt;   &lt;div id="resg-s1-37621" class="bucketwrap image large"&gt;             &lt;div     class="imagewrap has-source-dimensions"     data-crop-type=""     style="         --source-width: 5392;         --source-height: 3033;     " &gt;         &lt;picture&gt;             &lt;source srcset="https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/5392x3033+0+280/resize/400/quality/85/format/webp/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fe8%2Fa9%2F413b7f1646abb28f9429bd6b38cf%2Fgettyimages-2188254038.jpg 400w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/5392x3033+0+280/resize/600/quality/85/format/webp/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fe8%2Fa9%2F413b7f1646abb28f9429bd6b38cf%2Fgettyimages-2188254038.jpg 600w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/5392x3033+0+280/resize/800/quality/85/format/webp/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fe8%2Fa9%2F413b7f1646abb28f9429bd6b38cf%2Fgettyimages-2188254038.jpg 800w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/5392x3033+0+280/resize/900/quality/85/format/webp/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fe8%2Fa9%2F413b7f1646abb28f9429bd6b38cf%2Fgettyimages-2188254038.jpg 900w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/5392x3033+0+280/resize/1200/quality/85/format/webp/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fe8%2Fa9%2F413b7f1646abb28f9429bd6b38cf%2Fgettyimages-2188254038.jpg 1200w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/5392x3033+0+280/resize/1600/quality/85/format/webp/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fe8%2Fa9%2F413b7f1646abb28f9429bd6b38cf%2Fgettyimages-2188254038.jpg 1600w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/5392x3033+0+280/resize/1800/quality/85/format/webp/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fe8%2Fa9%2F413b7f1646abb28f9429bd6b38cf%2Fgettyimages-2188254038.jpg 1800w" data-template="https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/5392x3033+0+280/resize/{width}/quality/{quality}/format/{format}/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fe8%2Fa9%2F413b7f1646abb28f9429bd6b38cf%2Fgettyimages-2188254038.jpg" sizes="(min-width: 1300px) 763px, (min-width: 1025px) calc(100vw - 496px), (min-width: 768px) calc(100vw - 171px), calc(100vw - 30px)" class="img" type="image/webp" /&gt;             &lt;source srcset="https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/5392x3033+0+280/resize/400/quality/85/format/jpeg/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fe8%2Fa9%2F413b7f1646abb28f9429bd6b38cf%2Fgettyimages-2188254038.jpg 400w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/5392x3033+0+280/resize/600/quality/85/format/jpeg/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fe8%2Fa9%2F413b7f1646abb28f9429bd6b38cf%2Fgettyimages-2188254038.jpg 600w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/5392x3033+0+280/resize/800/quality/85/format/jpeg/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fe8%2Fa9%2F413b7f1646abb28f9429bd6b38cf%2Fgettyimages-2188254038.jpg 800w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/5392x3033+0+280/resize/900/quality/85/format/jpeg/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fe8%2Fa9%2F413b7f1646abb28f9429bd6b38cf%2Fgettyimages-2188254038.jpg 900w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/5392x3033+0+280/resize/1200/quality/85/format/jpeg/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fe8%2Fa9%2F413b7f1646abb28f9429bd6b38cf%2Fgettyimages-2188254038.jpg 1200w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/5392x3033+0+280/resize/1600/quality/85/format/jpeg/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fe8%2Fa9%2F413b7f1646abb28f9429bd6b38cf%2Fgettyimages-2188254038.jpg 1600w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/5392x3033+0+280/resize/1800/quality/85/format/jpeg/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fe8%2Fa9%2F413b7f1646abb28f9429bd6b38cf%2Fgettyimages-2188254038.jpg 1800w" data-template="https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/5392x3033+0+280/resize/{width}/quality/{quality}/format/{format}/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fe8%2Fa9%2F413b7f1646abb28f9429bd6b38cf%2Fgettyimages-2188254038.jpg" sizes="(min-width: 1300px) 763px, (min-width: 1025px) calc(100vw - 496px), (min-width: 768px) calc(100vw - 171px), calc(100vw - 30px)" class="img" type="image/jpeg" /&gt;             &lt;img src="https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/5392x3033+0+280/resize/1100/quality/50/format/jpeg/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fe8%2Fa9%2F413b7f1646abb28f9429bd6b38cf%2Fgettyimages-2188254038.jpg" data-template="https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/5392x3033+0+280/resize/{width}/quality/{quality}/format/{format}/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fe8%2Fa9%2F413b7f1646abb28f9429bd6b38cf%2Fgettyimages-2188254038.jpg" class="img" alt="Syrian residents in Turkey wave Syrian opposition flags as they celebrate the end of the Baath rule in Syria after rebel fighters took control of Damascus overnight, at the Fatih Mosque, in Istanbul, on December 8, 2024. Islamist-led rebels declared that they have taken Damascus in a lightning offensive on December 8, sending President Bashar al-Assad fleeing and ending five decades of Baath rule in Syria. (Photo by Yasin AKGUL / AFP) / &amp;quot;The erroneous mention[s] appearing in the metadata of this photo by Yasin AKGUL has been modified in AFP systems in the following manner: [Syrian opposition flag] instead of [Syrian flag]. Please immediately remove the erroneous mention[s] from all your online services and delete it (them) from your servers. If you have been authorized by AFP to distribute it (them) to third parties, please ensure that the same actions are carried out by them. Failure to promptly comply with these instructions will entail liability on your part for any continued or post notification usage. Therefore we thank you very much for all your attention and prompt action. We are sorry for the inconvenience this notification may cause and remain at your disposal for any further information you may require.&amp;quot; (Photo by YASIN AKGUL/AFP via Getty Images)" loading="lazy" /&gt;         &lt;/picture&gt; &lt;/div&gt; &lt;div class="credit-caption"&gt;     &lt;div class="caption-wrap"&gt;         &lt;div class="caption" aria-label="Image caption"&gt;             &lt;p&gt;                 Syrian residents in Turkey wave Syrian opposition flags as they celebrate the President Bashar al-Assad's rule in Syria after rebel fighters took control of Damascus overnight, at the Fatih Mosque, in Istanbul, on December 8, 2024.                 &lt;b class="credit" aria-label="Image credit"&gt;                                          Yasin Akgul/Getty Images/AFP                                      &lt;/b&gt;                 &lt;b class="hide-caption"&gt;&lt;b&gt;&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/b&gt;             &lt;/p&gt;         &lt;/div&gt;               &lt;b class="toggle-caption"&gt;&lt;b&gt;&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/b&gt;     &lt;/div&gt;       &lt;/div&gt;    &lt;/div&gt;    &lt;ul class="edTag"&gt;&lt;li&gt;🎧 &lt;strong&gt;Syria allowed Iran to set up a critical land bridge to Lebanon to funnel weapons to Hezbollah for many years&lt;/strong&gt;, NPR's Jackie Northam tells &lt;em&gt;Up First&lt;/em&gt;. With the antigovernment rebels in control of Syria, the strategic route is most likely off-limits to Iran, impacting its long-term goals in the region. &lt;a href="https://one.npr.org/?sharedMediaId=1219032781:1263544708"&gt;Iran had two primary agendas&lt;/a&gt;: to destroy Israel as a Jewish state and to counter any influence the U.S. has in the Middle East. Iran's regime may also be worried about a threat of upheaval from its population as they see what is happening in Syria, Northam says.&lt;/li&gt;&lt;/ul&gt;   &lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Several U.S. colleges are advising international students planning to leave the country for the holiday break to return before Inauguration Day to avoid issues at the border. &lt;/strong&gt;Universities, including USC, the University of Pennsylvania and Cornell, have contacted students as they prepare for President-elect Donald Trump's second term. &lt;br&gt;&lt;/p&gt;       &lt;ul class="edTag"&gt;&lt;li&gt;🎧 &lt;strong&gt;Kirk Carapezza from NPR network station GBH says he believes this decision is being made as school administrators and international students revisit Trump's track record.&lt;/strong&gt; During his first term, new foreign student enrollment dropped by 12%. Trump implemented a travel ban targeting majority-Muslim countries and briefly prohibited international students from remaining in the U.S. if they took only online classes during the pandemic. &lt;a href="https://one.npr.org/?sharedMediaId=1219032781:1263544708"&gt;Trump is now promising stricter policies&lt;/a&gt;, but there are no concrete proposals. Carapezza says that behind closed doors, administrators and students are anxious.&lt;/li&gt;&lt;/ul&gt;   &lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;For weeks, New Jersey residents have reported seeing dozens of drones flying in the night skies. &lt;/strong&gt;Officials have few concrete explanations about where the drones are coming from, who's flying them and why. The White House says there's &lt;a href="https://www.npr.org/2024/12/11/nx-s1-5226000/new-jersey-drones"&gt;no evidence that the drones pose a security threat&lt;/a&gt; or have any foreign ties, which has left many residents and officials with more questions. &lt;br&gt;&lt;/p&gt;   &lt;ul class="edTag"&gt;&lt;li&gt;🎧 &lt;strong&gt;The FBI and other federal agencies say there is an active investigation into the matter&lt;/strong&gt;, Giulia Heyward of NPR network station WNYC says. The federal government is sending specialized radar technology to local police departments in the state to help determine what is happening. Local New Jersey lawmakers have &lt;a href="https://one.npr.org/?sharedMediaId=1219032781:1263544708"&gt;expressed concern over how safe people really are&lt;/a&gt;, a contrast to federal and state officials who have said residents should remain calm and the drones pose no threats. The drones are starting to pop up in other states, including Pennsylvania, New York, Maryland and Connecticut.&lt;/li&gt;&lt;/ul&gt;       &lt;h3 class="edTag"&gt;Deep dive&lt;/h3&gt;   &lt;div id="resg-s1-37800" class="bucketwrap image large"&gt;             &lt;div     class="imagewrap has-source-dimensions"     data-crop-type=""     style="         --source-width: 2059;         --source-height: 1158;     " &gt;         &lt;picture&gt;             &lt;source srcset="https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/2059x1158+0+171/resize/400/quality/85/format/webp/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fc7%2F9c%2F550ce50f4ea5bc551cf4478af263%2Fgettyimages-1372478419.jpg 400w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/2059x1158+0+171/resize/600/quality/85/format/webp/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fc7%2F9c%2F550ce50f4ea5bc551cf4478af263%2Fgettyimages-1372478419.jpg 600w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/2059x1158+0+171/resize/800/quality/85/format/webp/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fc7%2F9c%2F550ce50f4ea5bc551cf4478af263%2Fgettyimages-1372478419.jpg 800w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/2059x1158+0+171/resize/900/quality/85/format/webp/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fc7%2F9c%2F550ce50f4ea5bc551cf4478af263%2Fgettyimages-1372478419.jpg 900w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/2059x1158+0+171/resize/1200/quality/85/format/webp/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fc7%2F9c%2F550ce50f4ea5bc551cf4478af263%2Fgettyimages-1372478419.jpg 1200w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/2059x1158+0+171/resize/1600/quality/85/format/webp/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fc7%2F9c%2F550ce50f4ea5bc551cf4478af263%2Fgettyimages-1372478419.jpg 1600w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/2059x1158+0+171/resize/1800/quality/85/format/webp/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fc7%2F9c%2F550ce50f4ea5bc551cf4478af263%2Fgettyimages-1372478419.jpg 1800w" data-template="https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/2059x1158+0+171/resize/{width}/quality/{quality}/format/{format}/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fc7%2F9c%2F550ce50f4ea5bc551cf4478af263%2Fgettyimages-1372478419.jpg" sizes="(min-width: 1300px) 763px, (min-width: 1025px) calc(100vw - 496px), (min-width: 768px) calc(100vw - 171px), calc(100vw - 30px)" class="img" type="image/webp" /&gt;             &lt;source srcset="https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/2059x1158+0+171/resize/400/quality/85/format/jpeg/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fc7%2F9c%2F550ce50f4ea5bc551cf4478af263%2Fgettyimages-1372478419.jpg 400w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/2059x1158+0+171/resize/600/quality/85/format/jpeg/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fc7%2F9c%2F550ce50f4ea5bc551cf4478af263%2Fgettyimages-1372478419.jpg 600w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/2059x1158+0+171/resize/800/quality/85/format/jpeg/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fc7%2F9c%2F550ce50f4ea5bc551cf4478af263%2Fgettyimages-1372478419.jpg 800w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/2059x1158+0+171/resize/900/quality/85/format/jpeg/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fc7%2F9c%2F550ce50f4ea5bc551cf4478af263%2Fgettyimages-1372478419.jpg 900w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/2059x1158+0+171/resize/1200/quality/85/format/jpeg/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fc7%2F9c%2F550ce50f4ea5bc551cf4478af263%2Fgettyimages-1372478419.jpg 1200w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/2059x1158+0+171/resize/1600/quality/85/format/jpeg/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fc7%2F9c%2F550ce50f4ea5bc551cf4478af263%2Fgettyimages-1372478419.jpg 1600w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/2059x1158+0+171/resize/1800/quality/85/format/jpeg/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fc7%2F9c%2F550ce50f4ea5bc551cf4478af263%2Fgettyimages-1372478419.jpg 1800w" data-template="https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/2059x1158+0+171/resize/{width}/quality/{quality}/format/{format}/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fc7%2F9c%2F550ce50f4ea5bc551cf4478af263%2Fgettyimages-1372478419.jpg" sizes="(min-width: 1300px) 763px, (min-width: 1025px) calc(100vw - 496px), (min-width: 768px) calc(100vw - 171px), calc(100vw - 30px)" class="img" type="image/jpeg" /&gt;             &lt;img src="https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/2059x1158+0+171/resize/1100/quality/50/format/jpeg/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fc7%2F9c%2F550ce50f4ea5bc551cf4478af263%2Fgettyimages-1372478419.jpg" data-template="https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/2059x1158+0+171/resize/{width}/quality/{quality}/format/{format}/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fc7%2F9c%2F550ce50f4ea5bc551cf4478af263%2Fgettyimages-1372478419.jpg" class="img" alt="Scientists have identified two types of brain cells in the abdomen that appear to control different aspects of digestion." loading="lazy" /&gt;         &lt;/picture&gt; &lt;/div&gt; &lt;div class="credit-caption"&gt;     &lt;div class="caption-wrap"&gt;         &lt;div class="caption" aria-label="Image caption"&gt;             &lt;p&gt;                 Scientists have identified two types of brain cells in the abdomen that appear to control different aspects of digestion.                 &lt;b class="credit" aria-label="Image credit"&gt;                                          inkoly/Getty Images/iStockphoto                                      &lt;/b&gt;                 &lt;b class="hide-caption"&gt;&lt;b&gt;&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/b&gt;             &lt;/p&gt;         &lt;/div&gt;               &lt;b class="toggle-caption"&gt;&lt;b&gt;&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/b&gt;     &lt;/div&gt;       &lt;/div&gt;    &lt;/div&gt;    &lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Scientists have identified two types of neurons in the abdomen&lt;/strong&gt; that appear to control parts of digestion. The finding, reported in the journal &lt;em&gt;Nature&lt;/em&gt;, helps explain how clusters of neurons in the body play a key role in the gut-brain connection. Just like in the brain, it &lt;a href="https://www.npr.org/2024/12/12/nx-s1-5225375/these-neurons-in-the-abdomen-help-form-the-gut-brain-connection"&gt;adds evidence that neurons in the body can take on specialized functions&lt;/a&gt;. &lt;br&gt;&lt;/p&gt;   &lt;ul class="edTag"&gt;&lt;li&gt;🧠 &lt;strong&gt;Although the research involved mice&lt;/strong&gt;, Yuki Oka, one of the study's authors, says human digestive tracts are similar and probably contain a similar system.&lt;/li&gt;&lt;li&gt;🧠 &lt;strong&gt;The study focused on the sympathetic nervous system, a subset of the peripheral nervous system &lt;/strong&gt;that becomes more active when the brain detects danger. As a result, your adrenaline goes up, and glucose levels in the blood rise.&lt;/li&gt;&lt;li&gt;🧠 &lt;strong&gt;The research supports scientific views that specialized neurons in the body play an important role &lt;/strong&gt;in the gut-brain connection, which impacts everything from hunger to mood.&lt;/li&gt;&lt;li&gt;🧠 &lt;strong&gt;Specialized neurons offer potential targets to treat&lt;/strong&gt; high blood pressure, depression, irritable bowel syndrome and more.&lt;/li&gt;&lt;/ul&gt;   &lt;h3 class="edTag"&gt;Weekend picks&lt;/h3&gt;   &lt;div id="resg-s1-34751" class="bucketwrap image large"&gt;             &lt;div     class="imagewrap has-source-dimensions"     data-crop-type=""     style="         --source-width: 1440;         --source-height: 810;     " &gt;         &lt;picture&gt;             &lt;source srcset="https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/1440x810+0+304/resize/400/quality/85/format/webp/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fa0%2F19%2F7e6634af492b8ca0d4197fb84240%2Fgabriela-ortiz-revolucion-diamantina-los-angeles-philharmonic-gustavo-dudamel.jpg 400w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/1440x810+0+304/resize/600/quality/85/format/webp/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fa0%2F19%2F7e6634af492b8ca0d4197fb84240%2Fgabriela-ortiz-revolucion-diamantina-los-angeles-philharmonic-gustavo-dudamel.jpg 600w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/1440x810+0+304/resize/800/quality/85/format/webp/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fa0%